   <h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Abortion law</h1> 
   <div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content"> 
    <div id="siteSub" class="noprint">
     From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
    </div>

       Laws that permit, prohibit or regulate abortion
      </div>

        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p><b>Abortion law</b> permits, prohibits, restricts, or otherwise regulates the availability of <a href="/wiki/Abortion" title="Abortion">abortion</a>. Abortion has been a <a href="/wiki/Abortion_debate" title="Abortion debate">controversial subject</a> in many societies throughout history on religious, moral, ethical, practical, and political grounds. It has been banned frequently and otherwise limited by law. However, abortions continue to be common in many areas, even where they are illegal. According to the <a href="/wiki/World_Health_Organization" title="World Health Organization">World Health Organization</a> (WHO), abortion rates are similar in countries where the procedure is legal and in countries where it is not,<sup id="cite_ref-kaiser_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-kaiser-1">[1]</a></sup> due to unavailability of modern <a href="/wiki/Contraceptives" class="mw-redirect" title="Contraceptives">contraceptives</a> in areas where abortion is illegal.<sup id="cite_ref-Singh_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Singh-2">[2]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Also according to the WHO, the number of abortions worldwide is declining due to increased access to <a href="/wiki/Birth_control" title="Birth control">contraception</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-kaiser_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-kaiser-1">[1]</a></sup> Almost two-thirds of the world's women currently reside in countries where abortion may be obtained on request for a broad range of <a href="/wiki/Social_issues" class="mw-redirect" title="Social issues">social</a>, <a href="/wiki/Economic" class="mw-redirect" title="Economic">economic</a>, or personal reasons. Abortion laws vary widely by country. A few countries have banned abortions entirely.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div id="toc" class="toc" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading">

      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/History_of_abortion" title="History of abortion">History of abortion</a>
      </div> 
      <table class="box-More_citations_needed_section plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove" role="presentation">
       <tbody>
        <tr>
         <td class="mbox-image">
          <div style="width:52px">
           <a href="/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png" decoding="async" width="50" height="39" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="399"></a>
          </div></td>
         <td class="mbox-text">
          <div class="mbox-text-span">
           This section <b>needs additional citations for <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability">verification</a></b>.<span class="hide-when-compact"> Please help <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit">improve this article</a> by <a href="/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners" title="Help:Referencing for beginners">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.</span> <small class="date-container"><i>(<span class="date">July 2017</span>)</i></small><small class="hide-when-compact"><i> (<a href="/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title="Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a>)</i></small>
          </div></td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table> 
      <p>Abortion has existed since ancient times, with natural <a href="/wiki/Abortifacient" title="Abortifacient">abortifacients</a> being found amongst a wide variety of tribal people and in most written sources. The earliest known records of abortion techniques and general reproductive regulation date as far back as 2700 BC in China and 1550 BC in Egypt.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup> Early texts contain no mention of abortion or abortion law. When it does appear, it is entailed in concerns about male <a href="/wiki/Property_rights" class="mw-redirect" title="Property rights">property rights</a>, preservation of social order, and the duty to produce fit citizens for the state or community. The harshest penalties were generally reserved for a woman who procured an abortion against her husband's wishes, and for slaves who produced abortion in a woman of high status. Religious texts often contained severe condemnations of abortion, recommending penance but seldom enforcing secular punishment. As a matter of <a href="/wiki/Common_law" title="Common law">common law</a> in <a href="/wiki/England" title="England">England</a> and the United States, abortion was illegal anytime after <a href="/wiki/Quickening" title="Quickening">quickening</a>—when the movements of the <a href="/wiki/Fetus" title="Fetus">fetus</a> could first be felt by the woman. Under the <a href="/wiki/Born_alive_rule" title="Born alive rule">born alive rule</a>, the fetus was not considered a "reasonable being" <i>in Rerum Natura</i>; and abortion was not treated as <a href="/wiki/Murder_in_English_law" title="Murder in English law">murder in English law</a>. </p>
      <p>In the 20th century, many Western countries began to codify abortion law or place further restrictions on the practice. <a href="/wiki/Anti-abortion_movement" class="mw-redirect" title="Anti-abortion movement">Anti-abortion movements</a>, also referred to as <i>Pro-life</i> movements, were led by a combination of groups opposed to abortion on moral grounds, and by medical professionals who were concerned about the danger presented by the procedure and the regular involvement of non-medical personnel in performing abortions. Nevertheless, it became clear that illegal abortions continued to take place in large numbers even where abortions were rigorously restricted. It was difficult to obtain sufficient evidence to prosecute the women and abortion doctors, and judges and juries were often reluctant to convict. For example, <a href="/wiki/Henry_Morgentaler" title="Henry Morgentaler">Henry Morgentaler</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Canadians" title="Canadians">Canadian</a> <a href="/wiki/Pro-choice" class="mw-redirect" title="Pro-choice">pro-choice</a> advocate, was never convicted by a jury. He was acquitted by a jury in the 1973 court case, but the acquittal was overturned by five judges on the <a href="/wiki/Quebec_Court_of_Appeal" title="Quebec Court of Appeal">Quebec Court of Appeal</a> in 1974. He went to prison, appealed, and was again acquitted. In total, he served 10 months, suffering a <a href="/wiki/Heart_attack" class="mw-redirect" title="Heart attack">heart attack</a> while in <a href="/wiki/Solitary_confinement" title="Solitary confinement">solitary confinement</a>. Many were also outraged at the invasion of privacy and the medical problems resulting from abortions taking place illegally in medically dangerous circumstances. Political movements soon coalesced around the legalization of abortion and liberalization of existing laws. </p>
      <p>By the mid 20th century, many countries had begun to liberalize abortion laws, at least when performed to protect the life of the woman and in some cases on woman's request. Under <a href="/wiki/Vladimir_Lenin" title="Vladimir Lenin">Vladimir Lenin</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union">Soviet Union</a> legalized abortions on request in 1920.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:0_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Bolsheviks" title="Bolsheviks">Bolsheviks</a> saw abortion as a social evil created by the capitalist system, which left women without the economic means to raise children, forcing them to perform abortions. The Soviet state initially preserved the tsarists ban on abortion, which treated the practice as premeditated murder. However, abortion had been practiced by Russian women for decades and its incidence skyrocketed further as a result of the <a href="/wiki/Russian_Civil_War" title="Russian Civil War">Russian Civil War</a>, which had left the country economically devastated and made it extremely difficult for many people to have children. The Soviet state recognized that banning abortion would not stop the practice because women would continue using the services of private abortionists. In rural areas, these were often old women who had no medical training, which made their services very dangerous to women's health. In November 1920 the Soviet regime legalized abortion in state hospitals. The state considered abortion as a temporary necessary evil, which would disappear in the future Communist society, which would be able to provide for all the children conceived.<sup id="cite_ref-Wendy_Z._Goldman_2004_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wendy_Z._Goldman_2004-10">[10]</a></sup> In 1936, <a href="/wiki/Joseph_Stalin" title="Joseph Stalin">Joseph Stalin</a> placed prohibitions on abortions, which restricted them to medically recommended cases only, in order to increase population growth after the enormous loss of life in <a href="/wiki/World_War_1" class="mw-redirect" title="World War 1">World War 1</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Russian_Civil_War" title="Russian Civil War">Russian Civil War</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Richard_Overy_2004_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Richard_Overy_2004-11">[11]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> In the 1930s, several countries (<a href="/wiki/Poland" title="Poland">Poland</a>, <a href="/wiki/Turkey" title="Turkey">Turkey</a>, <a href="/wiki/Denmark" title="Denmark">Denmark</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sweden" title="Sweden">Sweden</a>, <a href="/wiki/Iceland" title="Iceland">Iceland</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>) legalized abortion in some special cases (<a href="/wiki/Pregnancy_from_rape" title="Pregnancy from rape">pregnancy from rape</a>, threat to mother's health, fetal malformation). In 1948 abortion was legalized in Japan, 1952 in <a href="/wiki/Yugoslavia" title="Yugoslavia">Yugoslavia</a> (on a limited basis), and 1955 in the Soviet Union (on demand). Some Soviet allies (Poland, Hungary, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Romania) legalized abortion in the late 1950s under pressure from the Soviets.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>In the United Kingdom, the <a href="/wiki/Abortion_Act_1967" title="Abortion Act 1967">Abortion Act of 1967</a> clarified and prescribed abortions as legal up to 28 weeks (later reduced to 24 weeks). Other countries soon followed, including Canada (1969), the United States (1973 in most states, pursuant to <i><a href="/wiki/Roe_v._Wade" title="Roe v. Wade">Roe v. Wade</a></i>&nbsp;– the <a href="/wiki/U.S._Supreme_Court" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Supreme Court">U.S. Supreme Court</a> decision which legalized abortion nationwide), <a href="/wiki/Tunisia" title="Tunisia">Tunisia</a> (1973), Denmark (1973), Austria (1974), France (1975), Sweden (1975), New Zealand (1977), Italy (1978), the <a href="/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands">Netherlands</a> (1980), and Belgium (1990). However, these countries vary greatly in the circumstances under which abortion was to be permitted. In 1975, the West German Supreme Court <a href="/wiki/German_Federal_Constitutional_Court_abortion_decision" class="mw-redirect" title="German Federal Constitutional Court abortion decision">struck down</a> a law legalizing abortion, holding that they contradict the <a href="/wiki/Basic_Law_for_the_Federal_Republic_of_Germany" title="Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany">constitution</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Human_rights" title="Human rights">human rights</a> guarantees. In 1976, a law was adopted which enabled abortions up to 12 weeks. After Germany's <a href="/wiki/German_reunification" title="German reunification">reunification</a>, despite the legal status of abortion in <a href="/wiki/East_Germany" title="East Germany">former East Germany</a>, a compromise was reached which deemed most abortions up to 12 weeks legal. In jurisdictions governed under <a href="/wiki/Sharia_law" class="mw-redirect" title="Sharia law">sharia law</a>, abortion after the 120th day from conception (19 weeks from <a href="/wiki/Gestational_age" title="Gestational age">LMP</a>) is illegal, especially for those who follow the recommendations of the <a href="/wiki/Hanafi" title="Hanafi">Hanafi</a> legal school, while most jurists of the <a href="/wiki/Maliki" title="Maliki">Maliki</a> legal school "believe that ensoulment occurs at the moment of conception, and they tend to forbid abortion at any point [similar to the Roman Catholic Church]. The other schools hold intermediate positions. [..] The penalty prescribed for an illegal abortion varies according to particular circumstances involved. According to sharia, it should be limited to a fine that is paid to the father or heirs of the fetus".<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup> See also: <a href="/wiki/Islam_and_abortion" title="Islam and abortion">Islam and abortion</a>. </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="International_law">International law</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: International law">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>There are no international or multinational treaties that deal directly with abortion but <a href="/wiki/International_human_rights_law" title="International human rights law">human rights law</a> and <a href="/wiki/International_criminal_law" title="International criminal law">International criminal law</a> touch on the issues. </p>
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/Nuremberg_Military_Tribunal" class="mw-redirect" title="Nuremberg Military Tribunal">Nuremberg Military Tribunal</a> decided the case of United States v Greifelt &amp; others [1948] on the basis that abortion was a crime within its jurisdiction according to the law defining <a href="/wiki/Crimes_against_humanity" title="Crimes against humanity">crimes against humanity</a> and thus within its definition of murder and extermination.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/American_Convention_on_Human_Rights" title="American Convention on Human Rights">American Convention on Human Rights</a>, which in 2013 had 23 Latin American parties, declares human life as commencing with conception. In <a href="/wiki/Latin_America" title="Latin America">Latin America</a>, abortion is only legal in <a href="/wiki/Cuba" title="Cuba">Cuba</a> (1965) and <a href="/wiki/Uruguay" title="Uruguay">Uruguay</a> (2012).<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> It is also legal in <a href="/wiki/Mexico_City" title="Mexico City">Mexico City</a> and in the state of <a href="/wiki/Oaxaca" title="Oaxaca">Oaxaca</a> up to the twelfth week of pregnancy (the law on <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Mexico" title="Abortion in Mexico">abortion in Mexico</a> varies by <a href="/wiki/States_of_Mexico" class="mw-redirect" title="States of Mexico">state</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>In the 2010 case of <i><a href="/wiki/A,_B_and_C_v_Ireland" title="A, B and C v Ireland">A, B and C v Ireland</a></i>, the <a href="/wiki/European_Court_of_Human_Rights" title="European Court of Human Rights">European Court of Human Rights</a> found that the <a href="/wiki/European_Convention_on_Human_Rights" title="European Convention on Human Rights">European Convention on Human Rights</a> did not include a right to an abortion. </p>
      <p>In 2005 the <a href="/wiki/United_Nations_Human_Rights_Committee" title="United Nations Human Rights Committee">United Nations Human Rights Committee</a> ordered Peru to compensate a woman (known as K.L.) for denying her a medically indicated abortion; this was the first time a United Nations Committee had held any country accountable for not ensuring access to safe, legal abortion, and the first time the committee affirmed that abortion is a human right.<sup id="cite_ref-huffingtonpost.com_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffingtonpost.com-20">[20]</a></sup> K.L. received the compensation in 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-huffingtonpost.com_20-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-huffingtonpost.com-20">[20]</a></sup> In the 2016 case of <i><a href="/wiki/Mellet_v_Ireland" title="Mellet v Ireland">Mellet v Ireland</a></i>, the UN HRC found <a href="/wiki/Republic_of_Ireland" title="Republic of Ireland">Ireland</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_the_Republic_of_Ireland" title="Abortion in the Republic of Ireland">abortion laws</a> violated <a href="/wiki/International_Covenant_on_Civil_and_Political_Rights" title="International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights">International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights</a> because Irish law banned abortion in cases of fatal fetal abnormalities. </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="National_laws">National laws</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: National laws">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>While abortions are legal at least under certain conditions in almost all countries, these conditions vary widely. According to a <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> report with data gathered up to 2019,<sup id="cite_ref-UN2019report_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UN2019report-21">[21]</a></sup> abortion is allowed in 98% of countries in order to save a woman's life. Other commonly-accepted reasons are preserving physical (72%) or mental health (69%), in cases of rape or incest (61%), and in cases of fetal impairment (61%). Performing an abortion because of economic or social reasons is accepted in 37% of countries. Performing abortion only on the basis of a woman's request is allowed in 34% of countries, including in the United States, Canada, most <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">European</a> countries, and China.<sup id="cite_ref-UN2019report_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UN2019report-21">[21]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The exact scope of each legal ground also varies. For example, the laws of some countries cite health risks and fetal impairment as general grounds for abortion and allow a broad interpretation of such terms in practice, while other countries restrict them to a specific list of medical conditions or subcategories. Many countries also specify different gestational limits for when abortion can be done under each legal ground, for example 12 weeks for abortion on request and no limit to save a woman's life.<sup id="cite_ref-UN2019report_21-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UN2019report-21">[21]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>In some countries, additional procedures must be followed before the abortion can be carried out even if the basic grounds for it are met. For example, in Finland, where abortions are not granted based merely on a woman's request, approval for each abortion must be obtained from two doctors (or one in special circumstances).<sup id="cite_ref-UKAbortion1967_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UKAbortion1967-22">[22]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FinLaw1970_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FinLaw1970-23">[23]</a></sup> The vast majority, 90% of abortions in Finland are performed for socio-economic reasons.<sup id="cite_ref-tiitinen_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tiitinen-24">[24]</a></sup> How strictly all of the procedures dictated in the legislation are followed in practice is another matter. For example, in the United Kingdom, a <a href="/wiki/Care_Quality_Commission" title="Care Quality Commission">Care Quality Commission</a>'s report in 2012 found that several <a href="/wiki/National_Health_Service" title="National Health Service">NHS</a> clinics were circumventing the law, using forms pre-signed by one doctor, thus allowing abortions to patients who only met with one doctor.<sup id="cite_ref-CQC2012_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CQC2012-25">[25]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Summary_tables">Summary tables</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Summary tables">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>

      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Independent_countries">Independent countries</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Independent countries">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in all <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> <a href="/wiki/Member_states_of_the_United_Nations" title="Member states of the United Nations">member states</a> and <a href="/wiki/United_Nations_General_Assembly_observers" title="United Nations General Assembly observers">observer states</a> and some <a href="/wiki/List_of_states_with_limited_recognition" title="List of states with limited recognition">countries with limited recognition</a>. This table is mostly based on data compiled by the United Nations up to 2019,<sup id="cite_ref-UN2019data_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UN2019data-26">[26]</a></sup> with some updates, additions and clarifications citing other sources. </p> 
      <table class="wikitable sortable collapsible" style="font-size:small"> 
       <caption class="nowrap">

       </caption>

         <th style="width:70px">Rape</th> 
         <th style="width:70px">Fetal impairment</th> 
         <th style="width:70px">Economic or social</th> 
         <th style="width:70px">On request </th>
        </tr>

            <li id="cite_note-principle-27"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-6"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-7"><sup><i><b>h</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-8"><sup><i><b>i</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-9"><sup><i><b>j</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-10"><sup><i><b>k</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-11"><sup><i><b>l</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-12"><sup><i><b>m</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-13"><sup><i><b>n</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-14"><sup><i><b>o</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-15"><sup><i><b>p</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-16"><sup><i><b>q</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-17"><sup><i><b>r</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-18"><sup><i><b>s</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-19"><sup><i><b>t</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-20"><sup><i><b>u</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-21"><sup><i><b>v</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-principle_27-22"><sup><i><b>w</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">This ground is not explicitly mentioned in the law but it is accepted as a general legal principle.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-32"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The UN source of 2019 incorrectly cites a draft bill revising the Penal Code which would allow abortion on request.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[27]</a></sup> However, the version of the bill passed by the parliament in 2019 would allow abortion only in certain circumstances,<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[28]</a></sup> and the president vetoed the bill altogether in 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[29]</a></sup> The previous Penal Code, whose abortion law was summarized by the UN source of 2013,<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[30]</a></sup> remains in effect.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-34"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Including <a href="/wiki/States_and_territories_of_Australia" title="States and territories of Australia">external territories</a>.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-au-35"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-au_35-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-au_35-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-au_35-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Except in <a href="/wiki/South_Australia" title="South Australia">South Australia</a>.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-37"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-37">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Applies the laws of <a href="/wiki/Western_Australia" title="Western Australia">Western Australia</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[32]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-39"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-39">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Applies the laws of <a href="/wiki/Western_Australia" title="Western Australia">Western Australia</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[33]</a></sup></span> </li>

            <li id="cite_note-43"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-43">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Applies the laws of <a href="/wiki/New_South_Wales" title="New South Wales">New South Wales</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[35]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-bh-46"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-bh_46-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-bh_46-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-bh_46-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-bh_46-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-bh_46-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">The UN source marks it as a legal ground because the Penal Code explicitly prohibits abortion only if performed without the consent of the woman and of a medical practitioner.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[36]</a></sup> However, the decree regulating medical practice prohibits abortion unless the pregnancy threatens the woman's life.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[37]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-bd-47"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-bd_47-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-bd_47-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-bd_47-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-bd_47-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-bd_47-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">The UN source does not explicitly mark this legal ground for abortion but says that "menstrual regulation is available on request".</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-49"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-49">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">This ground is established by a regulation implementing a judicial decision, although it is not mentioned in the decision itself or in the law.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[38]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-50"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-50">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">This ground is not explicitly mentioned in the law but it is <a href="/wiki/ADPF_54" title="ADPF 54">established by judicial decision</a> only in the case of <a href="/wiki/Anencephaly" title="Anencephaly">anencephaly</a>.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-51"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-51">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Mainland_China" title="Mainland China">Mainland China</a>.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-52"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-52">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">A judicial pardon may be granted to the woman for an abortion on this ground.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-55"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-55">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">This ground is not explicitly mentioned in the law but it is accepted as a general legal principle, allowed by regulation and <a href="/wiki/Maputo_Protocol" title="Maputo Protocol">established by treaty</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-cd_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cd-53">[39]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[40]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-cd-57"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-cd_57-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-cd_57-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-cd_57-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">This ground is not explicitly mentioned in the law but it is <a href="/wiki/Maputo_Protocol" title="Maputo Protocol">established by treaty</a>, whose application is requested by the <a href="/wiki/Constitutional_Court_of_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo" title="Constitutional Court of the Democratic Republic of the Congo">Constitutional Court</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-cd_53-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cd-53">[39]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">[41]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-therapeutic-58"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-therapeutic_58-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-therapeutic_58-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">The UN source says that abortion is permitted for therapeutic purposes but is unclear whether it means only to save the woman's life or also to preserve her health.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-59"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-59">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Abortion is allowed in case of rape of a woman with a mental disability.</span> </li>

            <li id="cite_note-67"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-67">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The UN source does not explicitly mark it a social legal ground but says that abortion is permitted "if the woman is under marriage age or over the age of 40", or if "the pregnancy is the result of extramarital relations".</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-ci-70"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-ci_70-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ci_70-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">The UN source marks it as a legal ground but it is only <a href="/wiki/Maputo_Protocol" title="Maputo Protocol">established by treaty</a>, not by law and not implemented as of 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">[45]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">[46]</a></sup></span> </li>

            <li id="cite_note-84"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-84">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Only in <a href="/wiki/Mexico_City" title="Mexico City">Mexico City</a>, <a href="/wiki/Michoac%C3%A1n" title="Michoacán">Michoacán</a>, <a href="/wiki/Oaxaca" title="Oaxaca">Oaxaca</a> and <a href="/wiki/Yucat%C3%A1n" title="Yucatán">Yucatán</a>.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-85"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-85">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Only in <a href="/wiki/Mexico_City" title="Mexico City">Mexico City</a> and <a href="/wiki/Oaxaca" title="Oaxaca">Oaxaca</a>.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-88"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-88">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Including the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean_Netherlands" title="Caribbean Netherlands">Caribbean Netherlands</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86">[53]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87">[54]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-90"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-90">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">This ground is not explicitly mentioned in the law but it is established by judicial decision in the southern <a href="/wiki/States_of_Nigeria" title="States of Nigeria">states</a>.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-92"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-92">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Including <a href="/wiki/Svalbard" title="Svalbard">Svalbard</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">[56]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-poland-95"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-poland_95-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">On 22 October 2020, the <a href="/wiki/Constitutional_Tribunal_(Poland)" title="Constitutional Tribunal (Poland)">Constitutional Tribunal</a> ruled that abortion in case of fetal impairment was unconstitutional. The ruling is not effective until it is published in the <a href="/wiki/Dziennik_Ustaw" title="Dziennik Ustaw">Journal of Laws</a>, which has not yet occurred as of December 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">[57]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-94" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-94">[58]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-96"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-96">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The UN source does not explicitly mark it a social legal ground but says that the ground for risk to health includes "the pregnant woman's actual or reasonably foreseeable environment".</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-gbni-98"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-gbni_98-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-gbni_98-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Only in <a href="/wiki/Northern_Ireland" title="Northern Ireland">Northern Ireland</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-gbni_99-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gbni-99">[60]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-us-101"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-us_101-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-us_101-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-us_101-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-us_101-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-us_101-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">In some <a href="/wiki/U.S._state" title="U.S. state">states</a>, this ground is not explicitly mentioned in the law but it is <a href="/wiki/Roe_v._Wade" title="Roe v. Wade">established by judicial decision</a>.</span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-116"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-116">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The <a href="/wiki/Law_of_Vatican_City" title="Law of Vatican City">law of Vatican City</a> is primarily based on the <a href="/wiki/Canon_law_of_the_Catholic_Church" title="Canon law of the Catholic Church">canon law of the Catholic Church</a> and applies the <a href="/wiki/Zanardelli_Code" title="Zanardelli Code">Italian penal code</a> in force in 1929 with local modifications.<sup id="cite_ref-111" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111">[71]</a></sup> Both sources of law prohibit abortion without explicitly mentioning any exception.<sup id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112">[72]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-it1889_113-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-it1889-113">[73]</a></sup> The penal code lists the general principle of necessity to save one's life, which removes punishment for any crime,<sup id="cite_ref-it1889_113-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-it1889-113">[73]</a></sup> but the Church's official interpretation of <a href="/wiki/Canon_1398" title="Canon 1398">canon 1398</a> is more restrictive, allowing in such cases only <a href="/wiki/Indirect_abortion" title="Indirect abortion">indirect abortion</a> under the <a href="/wiki/Principle_of_double_effect" title="Principle of double effect">principle of double effect</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-114">[74]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115">[75]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-117"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-117">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The UN source does not explicitly mark it a social legal ground but says that abortion is permitted for risk to health of existing children of the woman.</span> </li> 
           </ol>
          </div> </td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Autonomous_jurisdictions">Autonomous jurisdictions</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Autonomous jurisdictions">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in autonomous jurisdictions not included in the previous table. </p> 
      <table class="wikitable sortable collapsible" style="font-size:small"> 
       <caption class="nowrap">
        Legal grounds on which abortion is permitted in other autonomous jurisdictions 
       </caption> 
       <tbody>
        <tr> 
         <th>Jurisdiction</th> 
         <th style="width:70px">Save life</th> 
         <th style="width:70px">Preserve health</th> 
         <th style="width:70px">Rape</th> 
         <th style="width:70px">Fetal impairment</th> 
         <th style="width:70px">Economic or social</th> 
         <th style="width:70px">On request </th>
        </tr>

         <td data-sort-value="Yes" style="background: #D2FFD2; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="table-yes2"><img alt="Yes" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Green_check.svg/13px-Green_check.svg.png" decoding="async" title="Yes" width="13" height="13" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Green_check.svg/20px-Green_check.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Green_check.svg/26px-Green_check.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="600"><sup id="cite_ref-tc_143-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tc-143">[g]</a></sup></td> 
         <td style="background:#F99;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;" class="table-no"><img alt="Dark Red x.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Dark_Red_x.svg/13px-Dark_Red_x.svg.png" decoding="async" width="13" height="13" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Dark_Red_x.svg/20px-Dark_Red_x.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Dark_Red_x.svg/26px-Dark_Red_x.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="600"></td>

      </table>

            <li id="cite_note-gg1-141"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-gg1_141-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-gg1_141-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">In <a href="/wiki/Alderney" title="Alderney">Alderney</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sark" title="Sark">Sark</a>, this ground is not explicitly mentioned in the law.<sup id="cite_ref-gg_139-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gg-139">[93]</a></sup> A judicial decision on an identical law in the parent country clarified that the law always implicitly allowed abortion at least to save the woman's life, and the decision allowed it also to preserve her health.<sup id="cite_ref-gb_140-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gb-140">[94]</a></sup> It is unclear whether Alderney and Sark apply only the original legal principle or also the judicial decision.</span> </li>

            <li id="cite_note-146"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-146">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">This ground is not explicitly mentioned in the law, but it is included by regulation in the ground for preserving physical or mental health.<sup id="cite_ref-hk_144-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hk-144">[95]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-145" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-145">[96]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-mp-153"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-mp_153-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-mp_153-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-mp_153-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-mp_153-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-mp_153-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-mp_153-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">The <a href="/wiki/Constitution_of_the_Northern_Mariana_Islands" class="mw-redirect" title="Constitution of the Northern Mariana Islands">territory's constitution</a> prohibits abortion "except as provided by law", and the territory has no law about the subject. However, according to an opinion issued by the <a href="/wiki/Attorney_General_of_the_Northern_Mariana_Islands" title="Attorney General of the Northern Mariana Islands">territory's attorney general</a>, U.S. judicial decisions on abortion apply to the territory, thus allowing abortion on request.<sup id="cite_ref-mp_151-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mp-151">[101]</a></sup> Yet, in practice, authorized medical providers in the territory perform abortions only to save the woman's life and possibly in case of rape.<sup id="cite_ref-152" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-152">[102]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-gumpas_120-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gumpas-120">[78]</a></sup></span> </li>

            <li id="cite_note-sx-163"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-sx_163-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-sx_163-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-sx_163-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-sx_163-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-sx_163-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Although illegal, the government does not prosecute abortions performed under rules similar to other countries, including on request.<sup id="cite_ref-awcwsx_123-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-awcwsx-123">[81]</a></sup></span> </li> 
            <li id="cite_note-tk-166"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-tk_166-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-tk_166-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">This ground is not explicitly mentioned in the law. The judicial handbook says that abortion is permitted for medical reasons but is unclear whether it means only to save the woman's life or also to preserve her health.<sup id="cite_ref-165" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-165">[110]</a></sup></span> </li>

      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Europe">Europe</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Europe">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:332px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Conscientious_objection_to_abortion_in_Europe.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Conscientious_objection_to_abortion_in_Europe.svg/330px-Conscientious_objection_to_abortion_in_Europe.svg.png" decoding="async" width="330" height="286" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Conscientious_objection_to_abortion_in_Europe.svg/495px-Conscientious_objection_to_abortion_in_Europe.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Conscientious_objection_to_abortion_in_Europe.svg/660px-Conscientious_objection_to_abortion_in_Europe.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="520"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Conscientious_objection_to_abortion_in_Europe.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div><a href="/wiki/Conscientious_objection_to_abortion" title="Conscientious objection to abortion">Conscientious objection to abortion</a> by doctors in Europe<sup id="cite_ref-EDJNet_169-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EDJNet-169">[113]</a></sup> 
         <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959">
         <div class="legend">
          <span class="legend-color" style="background-color:#A6CE39; color:black; -webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;Allowed
         </div> 
         <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959">
         <div class="legend">
          <span class="legend-color" style="background-color:#6F2C91; color:white; -webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;Not allowed
         </div>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>Despite a wide variation in the restrictions under which it is permitted, abortion is legal in most European countries. The exceptions are the mini-state of <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Malta" title="Abortion in Malta">Malta</a><sup id="cite_ref-maltanote_171-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-maltanote-171">[115]</a></sup> and the micro-states of <a href="/wiki/Vatican_City" title="Vatican City">Vatican City</a>, <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_San_Marino" title="Abortion in San Marino">San Marino</a>, <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Liechtenstein" title="Abortion in Liechtenstein">Liechtenstein</a> and <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Andorra" title="Abortion in Andorra">Andorra</a>, where abortion is illegal or severely restricted.<sup id="cite_ref-OstergrenBossé2011_172-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OstergrenBossé2011-172">[116]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Kelly_173-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kelly-173">[117]</a></sup> The other states with existent, but less severe restrictions are <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Poland" title="Abortion in Poland">Poland</a> and <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Monaco" title="Abortion in Monaco">Monaco</a>. All the remaining states make abortion legal on request or for social and economic reasons during the first trimester. When it comes to later-term abortions, there are very few with laws as liberal as those of the United States.<sup id="cite_ref-Jenkins2007_174-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jenkins2007-174">[118]</a></sup> Restrictions on abortion are most stringent in a few countries that are strongly observant of the <a href="/wiki/Catholic_faith" class="mw-redirect" title="Catholic faith">Catholic</a> religion.<sup id="cite_ref-OstergrenBossé2011_172-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-OstergrenBossé2011-172">[116]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="European_Union">European Union</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: European Union">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Most countries in the European Union allow abortion on demand during the <a href="/wiki/Pregnancy" title="Pregnancy">first trimester</a>, with Sweden and the Netherlands having more extended time limits.<sup id="cite_ref-MI2013-07-14_170-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MI2013-07-14-170">[114]</a></sup> After the first trimester, abortion is generally allowed only under certain circumstances, such as risk to woman's life or health, fetal defects or other specific situations that may be related to the circumstances of the conception or the woman's age. For instance, in Austria, second trimester abortions are allowed only if there is a serious risk to physical health of woman (that cannot be averted by other means); risk to mental health of woman (that cannot be averted by other means); immediate risk to life of woman (that cannot be averted by other means); serious fetal impairment (physical or mental); or if the woman is under 14 years of age. Some countries, such as Denmark, allow abortion after the first trimester for a variety of reasons, including socioeconomic ones, but a woman needs an authorization to have such an abortion.<sup id="cite_ref-175" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-175">[119]</a></sup> Similarly, in <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Finland" title="Abortion in Finland">Finland</a>, technically abortions even just up to 12 weeks require authorization from two doctors (unless special circumstances), but in practice the authorization is only a <a href="/wiki/Rubber_stamp_(politics)" title="Rubber stamp (politics)">rubber stamp</a> and it is granted if the mother simply does not wish to have a baby.<sup id="cite_ref-ramo_176-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ramo-176">[120]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Access to abortion in much of Europe depends not as much on the letter of the law, but on the prevailing social views which lead to the interpretation of the laws. In much of Europe, laws which allow a second-trimester abortion due to mental health concerns (when it is deemed that the woman's psychological health would suffer from the continuation of the pregnancy) have come to be interpreted very liberally, while in some areas it is difficult to have a legal abortion even in the early stages of pregnancy due to <a href="/wiki/Conscientious_objection_to_abortion" title="Conscientious objection to abortion">conscientious objection</a> by doctors refusing to perform abortions against their personal moral or religious convictions.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_177-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-177">[121]</a></sup> </p>
      <p><a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Malta" title="Abortion in Malta">Malta</a> is the only EU country that bans abortion in all cases and does not have an exception for situations where the woman's life is in danger. The law, however, is not strictly enforced in relation to instances where a pregnancy endangers the woman's life.<sup id="cite_ref-maltanote_171-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-maltanote-171">[115]</a></sup> </p>
      <p><a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Italy" title="Abortion in Italy">Abortion in Italy</a> was legalized in 1978.<sup id="cite_ref-178" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-178">[122]</a></sup> However, the law allows <a href="/wiki/Health_professional" title="Health professional">health professionals</a> to refuse to perform an abortion. This <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Italy#Conscientious_objection" title="Abortion in Italy">conscientious objection</a> has the practical effect of restricting access to abortion.<sup id="cite_ref-179" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-179">[123]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>In <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_the_Republic_of_Ireland" title="Abortion in the Republic of Ireland">Ireland</a>, before December 2018, abortion was illegal except cases where a woman's life was endangered by the continuation of her pregnancy. However, in a <a href="/wiki/Thirty-sixth_Amendment_of_the_Constitution_Bill_2018" class="mw-redirect" title="Thirty-sixth Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2018">2018 referendum</a> a large majority of Irish citizens voted to repeal the <a href="/wiki/Eighth_Amendment_of_the_Constitution_of_Ireland" title="Eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland">constitutional amendment</a> prohibiting legislation relating to the termination of non-life-threatening pregnancies; and the new law enacted (the <a href="/wiki/Health_(Regulation_of_Termination_of_Pregnancy)_Act_2018" title="Health (Regulation of Termination of Pregnancy) Act 2018">Health (Regulation of Termination of Pregnancy) Act 2018</a>) allows abortion on request up to 12 weeks of pregnancy, and in certain circumstances at later stages. <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Northern_Ireland" class="mw-redirect" title="Abortion in Northern Ireland">Abortion in Northern Ireland</a> was decriminalized on 22 October 2019.<sup id="cite_ref-180" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-180">[124]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Europe's formerly Communist countries have liberal abortion laws. An exception is <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Poland" title="Abortion in Poland">Poland</a>, a country with a strict abortion law. Abortion is allowed only in cases of risk to the life or health of the woman or when the pregnancy is a result of a criminal act (the criminal act has to be confirmed by a prosecutor). A doctor in Poland who performs an abortion which is deemed to not have a legal basis is subject to criminal prosecution, and, out of fear of prosecution, doctors avoid abortions, except in the most extreme circumstances.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> </p>
      <p>Most European countries have laws which stipulate that minor girls need their parents' consent or that the parents must be informed of the abortion. In most of these countries however, this rule can be circumvented if a committee agrees that the girl may be posed at risk if her parents find out about the pregnancy, or that otherwise it is in her best interests to not notify her parents. The interpretation in practice of these laws depends from region to region, as with the other abortion laws.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_177-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-177">[121]</a></sup> Some countries differentiate between younger pregnant minors and older ones, with the latter not subjected to parental restrictions (for example under or above 16).<sup id="cite_ref-181" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-181">[125]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>In countries where abortion is illegal or restricted, it is common for women to travel to neighboring countries with more liberal laws. It was estimated in 2007 that over 6,000 Irish women travelled to Great Britain to have abortions every year.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_177-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-177">[121]</a></sup> </p>
      <p><a href="/wiki/Poland" title="Poland">Poland</a>, the country with some of the strictest abortion laws in <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>, is currently in the process of further tightening the regulations begun in October 2020. A top court ruling imposed a near complete ban on abortions, where terminations in case of foetal defects were to be considered unconstitutional.<sup id="cite_ref-182" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-182">[126]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> independent <a href="/wiki/Human_rights" title="Human rights">human rights</a> experts criticized the ruling, and called for the Polish authorities to respect the rights of men and women, who were <a href="/wiki/October_2020_Polish_protests" class="mw-redirect" title="October 2020 Polish protests">protesting against the ruling</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-183" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-183">[127]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="United_States">United States</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: United States">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_the_United_States" title="Abortion in the United States">Abortion in the United States</a>
      </div> 
      <p>In 1973, the <a href="/wiki/U.S._Supreme_Court" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Supreme Court">U.S. Supreme Court</a> decision <i><a href="/wiki/Roe_v._Wade" title="Roe v. Wade">Roe v. Wade</a></i> legalized abortion nationwide. It established a minimal period during which abortion must be legal (with more or fewer restrictions throughout the pregnancy). This basic framework, modified in <i><a href="/wiki/Planned_Parenthood_v._Casey" title="Planned Parenthood v. Casey">Planned Parenthood v. Casey</a></i> (1992), is still in effect today. In accordance with <i>Planned Parenthood v. Casey</i>, states cannot place legal restrictions posing an <a href="/wiki/Undue_burden_standard" title="Undue burden standard">undue burden</a> for "the purpose or effect of placing a substantial obstacle in the path of a woman seeking an abortion of a nonviable fetus."<sup id="cite_ref-184" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-184">[128]</a></sup> Although this legal framework established by the Supreme Court is very liberal (particularly with regard to the gestational age), in practice the effective availability of abortion varies significantly from state to state.<sup id="cite_ref-Doan3_185-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Doan3-185">[129]</a></sup> On June 29, 2020, the U.S. Supreme Court reaffirmed abortion rights after striking down a Louisiana law limiting abortion.<sup id="cite_ref-186" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-186">[130]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Countries_with_more_restrictive_laws">Countries with more restrictive laws</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Countries with more restrictive laws">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Vigilia_por_la_votaci%C3%B3n_de_la_Ley_de_Interrupci%C3%B3n_Voluntaria_del_Embarazo_en_Paran%C3%A1_24.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Vigilia_por_la_votaci%C3%B3n_de_la_Ley_de_Interrupci%C3%B3n_Voluntaria_del_Embarazo_en_Paran%C3%A1_24.jpg/220px-Vigilia_por_la_votaci%C3%B3n_de_la_Ley_de_Interrupci%C3%B3n_Voluntaria_del_Embarazo_en_Paran%C3%A1_24.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Vigilia_por_la_votaci%C3%B3n_de_la_Ley_de_Interrupci%C3%B3n_Voluntaria_del_Embarazo_en_Paran%C3%A1_24.jpg/330px-Vigilia_por_la_votaci%C3%B3n_de_la_Ley_de_Interrupci%C3%B3n_Voluntaria_del_Embarazo_en_Paran%C3%A1_24.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Vigilia_por_la_votaci%C3%B3n_de_la_Ley_de_Interrupci%C3%B3n_Voluntaria_del_Embarazo_en_Paran%C3%A1_24.jpg/440px-Vigilia_por_la_votaci%C3%B3n_de_la_Ley_de_Interrupci%C3%B3n_Voluntaria_del_Embarazo_en_Paran%C3%A1_24.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5472" data-file-height="3648"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Vigilia_por_la_votaci%C3%B3n_de_la_Ley_de_Interrupci%C3%B3n_Voluntaria_del_Embarazo_en_Paran%C3%A1_24.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>Supporter of legalized abortion at a rally in <a href="/wiki/Paran%C3%A1,_Entre_R%C3%ADos" title="Paraná, Entre Ríos">Paraná, Argentina</a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>According to a report by <a href="/wiki/Women_on_Waves" title="Women on Waves">Women on Waves</a>, approximately 25% of the world's population lives in countries with "highly restrictive abortion laws" - that is, laws which either completely ban abortion, or allow it only to save the <a href="/wiki/Maternal_death" title="Maternal death">mother's life</a>. This category includes several countries in <a href="/wiki/Latin_America" title="Latin America">Latin America</a>, <a href="/wiki/Africa" title="Africa">Africa</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Middle_East" title="Middle East">Middle East</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Asia-Pacific" title="Asia-Pacific">Asia-Pacific</a> region, as well as <a href="/wiki/Malta" title="Malta">Malta</a> in <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-maltanote_171-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-maltanote-171">[115]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-187" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-187">[131]</a></sup> The Centre For Reproductive Rights report that 'The inability to access safe and legal abortion care impacts 700 million women of reproductive age' <sup id="cite_ref-188" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-188">[132]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Latin America is the region with the most restrictive abortion laws. Fewer than 3% of the women in this region live in countries with liberal abortion laws — that is, where abortion is permitted either without restriction as to reason or on socioeconomic grounds.<sup id="cite_ref-189" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-189">[133]</a></sup> Some of the countries of <a href="/wiki/Central_America" title="Central America">Central America</a>, notably <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_El_Salvador" title="Abortion in El Salvador">El Salvador</a>, have also come to international attention due to very forceful enforcement of the laws, including the incarceration of a gang rape victim for homicide when she gave birth to a stillborn son and was accused of attempting an illegal abortion.<sup id="cite_ref-190" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-190">[134]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-191" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-191">[135]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-192" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-192">[136]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Beginning_of_pregnancy_controversy">Beginning of pregnancy controversy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Beginning of pregnancy controversy">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Beginning_of_pregnancy_controversy" title="Beginning of pregnancy controversy">Beginning of pregnancy controversy</a>
      </div> 
      <p>Controversy over the beginning of pregnancy occurs in different contexts, particularly in a legal context, and is particularly discussed within the <a href="/wiki/Abortion_debate" title="Abortion debate">abortion debate</a> from the point of measuring the gestational age of the pregnancy. Pregnancy can be measured from a number of convenient points, including the day of last <a href="/wiki/Menstrual_cycle" title="Menstrual cycle">menstruation</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ovulation" title="Ovulation">ovulation</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fertilisation" title="Fertilisation">fertilization</a>, <a href="/wiki/Implantation_(human_embryo)" title="Implantation (human embryo)">implantation</a> and chemical detection. A common medical way to calculate <a href="/wiki/Gestational_age" title="Gestational age">gestational age</a> is to measure pregnancy from the first day of the last menstrual cycle.<sup id="cite_ref-198" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-198">[142]</a></sup> However, not all legal systems use this measure for the purpose of abortion law; for example countries such as <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Belgium" title="Abortion in Belgium">Belgium</a>, <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_France" title="Abortion in France">France</a>, <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_Luxembourg" title="Abortion in Luxembourg">Luxembourg</a> use the term "pregnancy" in the abortion law to refer to the time elapsed from the sexual act that led to conception, which is presumed to be 2 weeks after the end of the last menstrual period.<sup id="cite_ref-200" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-200">[144]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Exceptions_in_abortion_law">Exceptions in abortion law</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Exceptions in abortion law">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>Exceptions in abortion laws occur either in countries where abortion is, as a general rule illegal, or in countries which have abortion on request with gestational limits (for example if a country allows abortion on request until 12 weeks, it may create exceptions to this general gestation limit for later abortions in specific circumstances).<sup id="cite_ref-201" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-201">[145]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>There are a few exceptions commonly found in abortion laws. Legal domains which do not have abortion on demand will often allow it when the health of the mother is at stake. "Health of the mother" may mean something different in different areas: for example, prior to December 2018, the <a href="/wiki/Abortion_in_the_Republic_of_Ireland" title="Abortion in the Republic of Ireland">Republic of Ireland</a> allowed abortion only to save the life of the mother, whereas <a href="/wiki/United_States_anti-abortion_movement" title="United States anti-abortion movement">abortion opponents in the United States</a> argue health exceptions are used so broadly as to render a ban essentially meaningless.<sup id="cite_ref-202" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-202">[146]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Laws allowing abortion in cases of rape or incest often differ. For example, before <i><a href="/wiki/Roe_v._Wade" title="Roe v. Wade">Roe v. Wade</a></i>, thirteen <a href="/wiki/U.S._state" title="U.S. state">US states</a> allowed abortion in the case of either rape or incest, but only <a href="/wiki/Mississippi" title="Mississippi">Mississippi</a> permitted abortion of pregnancies due to rape, and no state permitted it for just <a href="/wiki/Incest" title="Incest">incest</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-203" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-203">[147]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Many<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Vagueness" title="Wikipedia:Vagueness"><span title="This information is too vague. (March 2019)">vague</span></a></i>]</sup> countries allow for abortion only through the first or second <a href="/wiki/Trimester_(pregnancy)" class="mw-redirect" title="Trimester (pregnancy)">trimester</a>, and some may allow abortion in cases of fetal defects, e.g., <a href="/wiki/Down_syndrome" title="Down syndrome">Down syndrome</a> or where the pregnancy is the result of a <a href="/wiki/Sexual_crime" class="mw-redirect" title="Sexual crime">sexual crime</a>. </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Other_related_laws">Other related laws</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Other related laws">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       Main article: <a href="/wiki/Legal_protection_of_access_to_abortion" title="Legal protection of access to abortion">Legal protection of access to abortion</a>
      </div> 
      <p>Laws in some countries with liberal abortion laws protect access to abortion services. Such legislation often seeks to guard <a href="/wiki/Abortion_clinic" title="Abortion clinic">abortion clinics</a> against <a href="/wiki/Blockade" title="Blockade">obstruction</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vandalism" title="Vandalism">vandalism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Picketing_(protest)" class="mw-redirect" title="Picketing (protest)">picketing</a>, and other actions, or to protect patients and employees of such facilities from threats and harassment. Other laws create a perimeter around a facility, known variously as a "buffer zone", "bubble zone", or "access zone". This area is intended to limit how close to these facilities demonstration by those who <a href="/wiki/Anti-abortion_movements" title="Anti-abortion movements">oppose abortion</a> can approach. Protests and other displays are restricted to a certain distance from the building, which varies depending upon the law, or are prohibited altogether. Similar zones have also been created to protect the homes of abortion providers and clinic staff. Bubble zone laws are divided into "fixed" and "floating" categories. Fixed bubble zone laws apply to the static area around the facility itself, and floating laws to objects in transit, such as people or <a href="/wiki/Car" title="Car">cars</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-cfr_204-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cfr-204">[148]</a></sup> Because of conflicts between <a href="/wiki/Anti-abortion" class="mw-redirect" title="Anti-abortion">anti-abortion</a> activists on one side and women seeking abortion and medical staff who provides abortion on the other side, some laws are quite strict: in <a href="/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">South Africa</a> for instance, any person who prevents the lawful termination of a pregnancy or obstructs access to a facility for the termination of a pregnancy faces up to 10 years in prison (section 10.1 (c) of the Choice on Termination of Pregnancy Act<sup id="cite_ref-205" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-205">[149]</a></sup>). </p>
      <p>On 3 November 2020, an association of 20 Kenyan charities urged the government of <a href="/wiki/Kenya" title="Kenya">Kenya</a> to withdraw from the <a href="/wiki/Geneva_Consensus_Declaration" title="Geneva Consensus Declaration">Geneva Consensus Declaration</a> (GCD), a US-led international accord that sought to limit access to abortion for girls and women around the world. GCD was signed by 33 nations, on 22 October 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-206" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-206">[150]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Case_law">Case law</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Case law">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>Australia </p> 
      <ul>
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/R_v_Davidson" title="R v Davidson">R v Davidson</a> (Menhennitt ruling)</i> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/vic/VicRp/1969/85.html">[1969] VicRp 85</a>, [1969] <a href="/wiki/Victorian_Reports" title="Victorian Reports">VR</a> 667, <a href="/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_Victoria" title="Supreme Court of Victoria">Supreme Court</a> (Vic, Australia).</li> 
       <li><i>R v Sood (No 3)</i> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/nsw/NSWSC/2006/762.html">[2006] NSWSC 762</a>, <a href="/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_New_South_Wales" title="Supreme Court of New South Wales">Supreme Court</a> (NSW, Australia)</li>
      </ul> 
      <p>Canada </p> 
      <ul>

      <ul>

      </ul> 
      <p>South Africa </p> 
      <ul>
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Christian_Lawyers_Association_v_Minister_of_Health" title="Christian Lawyers Association v Minister of Health">Christian Lawyers Association v Minister of Health</a></i> (1998)</li>
      </ul> 
      <p>United Kingdom </p> 
      <ul>
       <li><i><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.supremecourt.uk/cases/docs/uksc-2017-0131-judgment.pdf">Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission v Department of Justice</a></i> (2018)</li>
      </ul> 
      <p>United States </p> 
      <ul>
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Roe_v._Wade" title="Roe v. Wade">Roe v. Wade</a></i> (1973)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Doe_v._Bolton" title="Doe v. Bolton">Doe v. Bolton</a></i> (1973)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/H._L._v._Matheson" title="H. L. v. Matheson">H. L. v. Matheson</a></i> (1981)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/City_of_Akron_v._Akron_Center_for_Reproductive_Health" title="City of Akron v. Akron Center for Reproductive Health">City of Akron v. Akron Center for Reproductive Health</a></i> (1983)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Webster_v._Reproductive_Health_Services" title="Webster v. Reproductive Health Services">Webster v. Reproductive Health Services</a></i> (1989)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Hodgson_v._Minnesota" title="Hodgson v. Minnesota">Hodgson v. Minnesota</a></i> (1990)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Planned_Parenthood_v._Casey" title="Planned Parenthood v. Casey">Planned Parenthood v. Casey</a></i> (1992)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Bray_v._Alexandria_Women%27s_Health_Clinic" title="Bray v. Alexandria Women's Health Clinic">Bray v. Alexandria Women's Health Clinic</a></i> (1993)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Stenberg_v._Carhart" title="Stenberg v. Carhart">Stenberg v. Carhart</a></i> (2000)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/McCorvey_v._Hill" title="McCorvey v. Hill">McCorvey v. Hill</a></i> (2004)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Ayotte_v._Planned_Parenthood_of_New_England" class="mw-redirect" title="Ayotte v. Planned Parenthood of New England">Ayotte v. Planned Parenthood of New England</a></i> (2006)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Gonzales_v._Carhart" title="Gonzales v. Carhart">Gonzales v. Carhart</a></i> (2007)</li> 
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/Whole_Woman%27s_Health_v._Hellerstedt" title="Whole Woman's Health v. Hellerstedt">Whole Woman's Health v. Hellerstedt</a></i> (2016)</li>
      </ul> 
      <p><a href="/wiki/European_Court_of_Human_Rights" title="European Court of Human Rights">European Court of Human Rights</a> </p> 
      <ul>
       <li><i><a href="/wiki/A._B._and_C._v._Ireland" class="mw-redirect" title="A. B. and C. v. Ireland">A. B. and C. v. Ireland</a></i> (2009)</li>

      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Abortion_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

        <li id="cite_note-Singh-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Singh_2-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Singh, Susheela et al. <i><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.guttmacher.org/pubs/AddingItUp2009.pdf">Adding it Up: The Costs and Benefits of Investing in Family Planning and Newborn Health</a></i>, pages 17, 19, and 27 (New York: Guttmacher Institute and United Nations Population Fund 2009): "Some 215 million women in the developing world as a whole have an unmet need for modern contraceptives…. If the 215 million women with unmet need used modern family planning methods....[that] would result in about 22 million fewer unplanned births; 25 million fewer abortions; and seven million fewer miscarriages....If women’s contraceptive needs were addressed (and assuming no changes in abortion laws)...the number of unsafe abortions would decline by 73% from 20 million to 5.5 million." A few of the findings in that report were subsequently changed, and are available at: "<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.guttmacher.org/pubs/FB-AIU-summary.pdf">Facts on Investing in Family Planning and Maternal and Newborn Health</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120324101905/http://www.guttmacher.org/pubs/FB-AIU-summary.pdf">Archived</a> March 24, 2012, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>" (Guttmacher Institute 2010).</span> </li>

        <li id="cite_note-198"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-198">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Some examples of <a href="/wiki/Gestational_age" title="Gestational age">gestational age</a> calculated from the first day of the last menstrual cycle:<sup id="cite_ref-193" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-193">[137]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-194" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-194">[138]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-195" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-195">[139]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-196" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-196">[140]</a></sup>}<sup id="cite_ref-197" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-197">[141]</a></sup></span> </li> 
        <li id="cite_note-199"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-199">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://legilux.public.lu/eli/etat/leg/loi/2014/12/17/n2/jo">"Loi du 17 décembre 2014 portant modification 1) du Code pénal et 2) de la loi du 15 novembre 1978 relative à l'information sexuelle, à la prévention de l'avortement clandestin et à la réglementation de l'interruption volontaire de grossesse. - Legilux"</a>. <i>legilux.public.lu</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=legilux.public.lu&amp;rft.atitle=Loi+du+17+d%C3%A9cembre+2014+portant+modification+1%29+du+Code+p%C3%A9nal+et+2%29+de+la+loi+du+15+novembre+1978+relative+%C3%A0+l%27information+sexuelle%2C+%C3%A0+la+pr%C3%A9vention+de+l%27avortement+clandestin+et+%C3%A0+la+r%C3%A9glementation+de+l%27interruption+volontaire+de+grossesse.+-+Legilux&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Flegilux.public.lu%2Feli%2Fetat%2Fleg%2Floi%2F2014%2F12%2F17%2Fn2%2Fjo&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAbortion+law" class="Z3988"></span>
          <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r982806391"></span> </li> 
        <li id="cite_note-200"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-200">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">For example Luxembourg abortion law states: "Avant la fin de la 12e semaine de grossesse ou avant la fin de la 14e semaine d’aménorrhée[...]" which translates to "Before the end of the 12th week of pregnancy or before the end of the 14th week of <a href="/wiki/Amenorrhea" title="Amenorrhea">amenorrhea</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-199" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-199">[143]</a></sup></span> </li> 
        <li id="cite_note-201"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-201">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFhelsedepartementet2000" class="citation web cs1">helsedepartementet, Sosial- og (18 May 2000). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.regjeringen.no/no/dokumenter/about-the-abortion-act/id419252/">"About the Abortion Act"</a>. <i>Government.no</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Government.no&amp;rft.atitle=About+the+Abortion+Act&amp;rft.date=2000-05-18&amp;rft.aulast=helsedepartementet&amp;rft.aufirst=Sosial-+og&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.regjeringen.no%2Fno%2Fdokumenter%2Fabout-the-abortion-act%2Fid419252%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAbortion+law" class="Z3988"></span>

        <li id="cite_note-203"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-203">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.pewstates.org/projects/stateline/headlines/states-probe-limits-of-abortion-policy2-85899387496">"States probe limits of abortion policy"</a>. <i>Stateline</i>.
